1.7.10 and 1.8.8 have different constructors for scaled resolution. You can add a new constructor for ScaledResolution to make it like 1.8.8

```java
public ScaledResolution(Minecraft mc) {
this(mc, mc.displayWidth, mc.displayHeight);
}
```

1.12.2 is a special snowflake and adds bad checks when comparing keybinds.

In your keybinds class, replace the compareto function with this

```java
public int compareTo(KeyBinding p_compareTo_1_) {
if (this.keyCategory.equals(p_compareTo_1_.keyCategory)) return I18n.format(this.keyDescription).compareTo(I18n.format(p_compareTo_1_.keyDescription));
Integer tCat = field_193627_d.get(this.keyCategory);
Integer oCat = field_193627_d.get(p_compareTo_1_.keyCategory);
if (tCat == null && oCat != null) return 1;
if (tCat != null && oCat == null) return -1;
if (tCat == null && oCat == null) return I18n.format(this.keyCategory).compareTo(I18n.format(p_compareTo_1_.keyCategory));
return  tCat.compareTo(oCat);
}
```

Looks like a decompile error, where there are two classes called Matrix4F, and eclipse is confused which one needs to be used. To fix this, change 
```java
public Matrix4f getMatrix()
{
return Reflector.ForgeHooksClient_getMatrix.exists() ? (javax.vecmath.Matrix4f)Reflector.call(Reflector.ForgeHooksClient_getMatrix, new Object[] {this}): new Matrix4f(this.getMatrix());
}
```
To:
```java
public javax.vecmath.Matrix4f getMatrix()
{
return Reflector.ForgeHooksClient_getMatrix.exists() ? (javax.vecmath.Matrix4f)Reflector.call(Reflector.ForgeHooksClient_getMatrix, new Object[] {this}): new javax.vecmath.Matrix4f(this.getMatrix());
}
```
